# Role: authorization-engineer

> **Owns:** Role-based access control (Admin / Reviewer / User) — deciding *what an authenticated user is allowed to do*, as distinct from `authentication-engineer` who decides *whether they're logged in at all*.
> Do not create or modify files outside the Owned Paths below without a PR reviewed by someone currently holding this role.

## Role Charter
Every other role's protected routes and gated UI depend on this role's middleware and guard component staying correct and stable. This is a small but high-blast-radius surface — treat interface changes here as breaking changes requiring cross-role coordination.

## Owned Paths
```
src/middleware/rbac.middleware.ts
src/components/guards/RequireRole.tsx
```

## Project Context
- Roles in the system: `Admin` | `Reviewer` | `User`
- `authenticate` (from `authentication-engineer`) always runs before `requireRole` in the middleware chain.

## Strict Rules
1. `src/middleware/rbac.middleware.ts` is imported by every other backend role — never break its exported interface (`requireRole`) without coordinating across all roles.
2. `RequireRole.tsx` is the only sanctioned way to gate a page/component by role on the frontend — do not let other roles hand-roll their own role checks in components.
3. Role checks must always fail closed (deny by default) on missing or malformed `req.user`.

```typescript
// src/middleware/rbac.middleware.ts
export const requireRole = (...roles: UserRole[]) =>
  (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
    if (!roles.includes(req.user?.role)) {
      return res.status(403).json(errorResponse('Insufficient permissions'));
    }
    next();
  };

// Usage in routes (other roles' route files)
router.get('/admin/users', authenticate, requireRole('Admin'), adminController.listUsers);
router.get('/reviewer/articles/pending', authenticate, requireRole('Reviewer', 'Admin'), reviewerController.listPending);
```

